    <entry>
        <text>ille... illius... ille...</text>
        <reference>1.7.3</reference>
        <reference>1.7.7</reference>
        <reference>1.9.1</reference>
        <comment>Referring back to the <span class="link lt" onclick="refer('1.6.3')">deus</span> (l. 6) to whom Tityrus attributes his new-found leisure.
</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry>
        <text>malum hoc</text>
        <reference>1.16.2</reference>
        <reference>1.16.3</reference>
        <comment>The death of the twin kids ([gemellos]{.lt}) is the evil Meliboeus is referring to.
</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry>
        <text>de caelo tactas</text>
        <reference>1.17.1</reference>
        <reference>1.17.2</reference>
        <reference>1.17.3</reference>
        <comment>lit. "struck from the sky", i.e. "by lightning"
</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry>
        <text>Musam meditaris</text>
        <reference>1.2.3</reference>
        <reference>1.2.4</reference>
        <comment><p><span onclick="refer('1.2.3--1.2.4')" class="link lt">Musam meditaris</span> can mean either "you are considering the Muse", or "you are practising a song"</p>
</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry>
        <text>silvestrem musam</text>
        <reference>1.2.1</reference>
        <reference>1.2.3</reference>
        <comment>‘woodland song’, the woodland being the forest pasture where the shepherds feed their flocks.</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry>
        <text>tenui avena</text>
        <reference>1.2.2</reference>
        <reference>1.2.5</reference>
        <comment>‘the slender oat’, i.e. the rustic pipe. (So the English pastoral poets speak of ‘oaten stop’, ‘oaten pipe’.)</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry>
        <text>tu, Tityre</text>
        <reference>1.4.4</reference>
        <reference>1.4.5</reference>
        <comment>Notice the pretty artifice, whereby he begins and ends with Tityrus.</comment>
    </entry>
    <entry>
        <text>lentus</text>
        <reference>1.4.6</reference>
        <comment>‘at ease’</comment>
    </entry>
